type="local">Baby steps in higher domain theory</fr:link> › 2-dimensional domain theory for concurrency (II)</fr:title><fr:taxon>Slide</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha ]]></fr:tex> be an “action”, and consider the two processes <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha \star ]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha .\varnothing  + \alpha \star ]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p><beamer:pause
xmlns:beamer="http://ctan.org/pkg/beamer" /><fr:p>We have <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {Traces}{\mathopen {}\left (\alpha \star \right )\mathclose {}} = {\mathopen {}\left \{\varepsilon , \alpha , \alpha .\alpha ,\ldots \right \}\mathclose {}}=\mathbf {Traces}{\mathopen {}\left (\alpha .\varnothing  + \alpha \star \right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p><beamer:pause
xmlns:beamer="http://ctan.org/pkg/beamer" /><fr:p>But the process <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha \star ]]></fr:tex> can never get stuck, whereas <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha .\varnothing  + \alpha \star ]]></fr:tex> gets stuck if it proceeds along the left branch.</fr:p><beamer:pause
xmlns:beamer="http://ctan.org/pkg/beamer" /><fr:p>Thus trace equivalence is highly un-physical. To deal with this, we generalise the information <fr:em>order</fr:em> to a category in which bisimulation can be expressed. <fr:strong>Idea: non-determinism must be modelled by a <fr:em>van Kampen</fr:em> colimit (e.g. disjoint coproduct).</fr:strong></fr:p><fr:p>See <fr:link
href="joyal-nielsen-winskel-1996.xml"
title="Bisimulation from open maps"
addr="joyal-nielsen-winskel-1996"
type="local">Joyal, Nielsen and Winskel (1996)</fr:link> and <fr:link
href="cattani-winskel-2005.xml"
title="Profunctors, open maps and bisimulation"
addr="cattani-winskel-2005"
type="local">Cattani and Winskel (2005)</fr:link>.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree
